    "projects": [
        {
            "title": "Master Thesis: Compositional zoned magma chamber source for both Cu-Mo-Au porphyry stocks and comtemporaneous volcanic equivalents, Bajo de Alumbrera, Argentina",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 8,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2015
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 8,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2015
                }
            },
            "description": "The geochemical identical and cotemporaneous ignimbritic volcanic units of the Bajo de Alumbrera porphyry Cu stocks in the Upper Miocene Farrall\u00f3n Negro Volcanic Complex in NW Argentin are studied. New data is presented on bulk geochemical and Nd, Sr and Pb isotopic compositions of unaltered juvenile clasts. Micronanalytical work on the major phenocrysts constituents was performed on both the porphyries and their volcanic counterparts.  Aided by zircon U/Pb measurements and volcano-sedimentary facies analysis, the unit could be subdivided into five subunits. These five ignimbritic subunits show remarkable geochemical gradients which can be attributed to eruption from a vertically zoned magma chamber. The observed gradients in whole rock geochemistry and crystallinities, the presence of significant amounts of layered juvenile clasts, the widespread presence of crystal clots, that are interpreted to be of cumulate nature, throughout the unit could all be attributed to an magma chamber were protracted fractional crystallization leaded to the formation of a cumulate crystal mush at the base of the eruptible reservoir. From such a reservoir highly evolved and water rich melts were extracted that formed the porphyry intrusions. The isotopic variation shows a mix between crustal and mantle source regions and trace elements show the necessity of amphibole fractionation at higher depth. Equigranular quench textured gabbroic enclaves with chilled margins, the abundance of sieve textured plagioclase and simple zoned amphibole, the high variabilities in An-content in plagioclase and Al in the amphibole, the presence of abundant dissolution surfaces in many plagioclase crystals and patchy zoned plagioclase, resorbed quartz and the presence of cumulate crystal clots of mafic origin with sector zoned clino-pyroxene and high Al-amphibole all indicate that open system magmatic processes such as recharge are equally dominant in the porphyry ore generating upper crustal magma chamber.",
